In this article, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. proclaims May 2022 as National Mental Health Awareness Month in the United States. He emphasizes the importance of mental health and its impact on individuals, families, and communities. The COVID-19 pandemic has worsened mental health conditions, leading to a crisis across the country, particularly affecting communities of color, frontline workers, healthcare workers, individuals with eating disorders, and young people. The article highlights the role of social media in exacerbating mental health challenges, especially among young women. It also mentions the disproportionate risk of suicide among American Indians, Alaska Natives, Black youth, and LGBTQI+ youth. The article acknowledges the barriers to accessing mental health treatment, such as insufficient mental health providers and stigma surrounding seeking help. President Biden's administration is committed to transforming mental health care by investing in mental health and substance use care, expanding access to care through virtual options, and integrating mental health treatment into primary care. The Surgeon General has released an advisory on protecting youth mental health, emphasizing the harms of digital technologies and calling for stronger privacy protections and restrictions on targeted advertising to children. Suicide prevention and crisis care infrastructure are also being strengthened. The article concludes with a call for individuals and various organizations to support those with mental health conditions, learn the warning signs of emotional distress and suicide, engage in supportive dialogue, and fight prejudice and negative attitudes. The National Suicide Prevention Lifeline is provided as a resource for immediate assistance.